{{Infobox storm | name = Fort Smith, Arkansas tornado | image = Fort Smith, Arkansas 1898 tornado damage.jpg | alt = | caption = Destroyed homes in Fort Smith | type = Tornado outbreak | active = January 11–12, 1898 | lowest pressure = | lowest temperature = | tornadoes = ≥2 | fujitascale = possibly F4 | tornado duration = >1 hour | highest winds = | hail = <!-- unused? --> | gusts = | maximum snow = | power outages = | total fatalities = 55 fatalities, 113 injuries | damages = $450,000 (1898 [[United States dollar|USD]])<ref name=MWR>http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/mwr/026/mwr-026-01-0018.pdf</ref> | affected = | current advisories = | enhanced = | notes = }}
The '''1898 Fort Smith, Arkansas tornado''' was a [[tornado]] which struck the city of [[Fort Smith, Arkansas]] during the night of Tuesday, January 11, 1898. It touched down about 100 miles to the southwest, and struck the city around midnight, killing 55 people and injuring 113. The twister nearly destroyed the city's newly constructed [[Fort Smith High School]] that opened in fall 1897.
It is tied for the deadliest tornado ever to strike the state of Arkansas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tornadoproject.com/alltorns/worstts.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-05-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514002740/http://www.tornadoproject.com/alltorns/worstts.htm |archivedate=2008-05-14 |df= }}</ref> Both tornadoes (1898, 1949) were estimated to be rated F4 on the [[Fujita scale]].<ref>http://www.ericsweatherlibrary.com/f4f5/f4-f5-tornadoes/</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Grazulis |first=Thomas P. |authorlink=Thomas P. Grazulis |title=Significant Tornadoes 1680-1991. A Chronology and Analysis of Events |publisher=The Tornado Project of Environmental Films |pages=681-682, 941|date=July 1993 |location=St. Johnsbury, VT |isbn=1-879362-03-1 }}</ref> Another tornado was also reported around 11pm that night in [[Alma, Arkansas]].<ref name="MWR"/>
