The '''Glashow resonance''', put forward by [[Sheldon Lee Glashow|Sheldon L. Glashow]] in 1959, is the resonant formation of the [[W boson]] in antineutrino-electron collisions: {{SubatomicParticle|Electron antineutrino}} + {{SubatomicParticle|Electron-}} → {{SubatomicParticle|W boson-}}.<ref>S. L. Glashow, Phys. Rev. 118 (1960) 316-317.</ref> The threshold antineutrino energy for this process (for the electron at rest in the laboratory frame) is 6.3 [[electronvolt|PeV]]. This process is considered for the detection and studies of high-energy cosmic neutrinos at the [[IceCube Neutrino Observatory|IceCube experiment]], at the [[ANTARES (telescope)|ANTARES neutrino telescope]], and at the [[KM3NeT| KM3NeT neutrino telescope]].

