The '''karozzin''' is a [[Malta|Maltese]] traditional mode of transport<ref>{{Cite book |title=The second world war: a world in flames |first=Max |last=Hastings |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YbOchL1LDSIC&pg=PA219&dq=karozzin&hl=en&ei=gJXOTNDmEMmj4Qah1PTcDA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CDwQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=karozzin&f=false |page=220 |year=2004 |publisher=Osprey |isbn=1-84176-830-8 }}</ref> consisting of a carriage pulled by a horse or pair of horses. It was once popular for general transit and is still used in ceremonies such as funerals, and as a tourist attraction. It is mostly found at [[Mdina]] and [[Valletta]], and dates to the mid-nineteenth century.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LRGrRy7S750C&pg=PA60&dq=karozzin&hl=en&ei=gJXOTNDmEMmj4Qah1PTcDA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=karozzin&f=false |title=Malta |publisher=Marshall Cavendish |year=2000 |first=Sean |last=Sheehan |page=61 |isbn=0-7614-0993-9 }}</ref>

